Mirashi prints taittirīya in l14 with a single initial t. Gupte and Sircar, correctly, read ttai. 
--><!-- 
In l14 Mirashi apparently reads apyaputrāputrāṇā without an anusvāra, and emends to saputrāputrāṇā, also without a final anusvāra unless it was lost in my scan [in fact, he probably does print an anusvāra in both his original and his emended reading; Lielukhine's digital text has an anusvāra]. He also emends the preceding m of °nām to anusvāra. He translates "to the Brāhmaṇas ... of the Parāśara gotra and the Taittirīya śākhā, whether they have or do not have sons"; footnote to ...: names omitted inadvertently. I have no better solution, but all this seems rather cheesy. The words of the whole passage seem jumbled up. Could the intent have been saputrapautrāṇām for this particular bit? 
--><!-- 
In l15 Mirashi omits pura. His translation is "together with a farm-house situated in it"; this does not reveal whether he read pura and the omission is a typo, or if he overlooked the word somehow. Gupte and Sircar do not omit the word. 
--><!-- 
In l15 I emend niveśane to niveśanena with Mirashi and Sircar. Gupte, however, keeps niveśane and reads saha in compound with karṣaka-niveśana. He translates abhyantarapuraniveśane as "while our camp is located here", which is strange; and he takes catvārabhuktakābhoga to be the name of the field that was donated. 
--><!-- 
After saha in l15 there seems to be a punctuation dot (short dash), or if this is a random dot, then there is a space of about half a character. Not noted by Mirashi and not transcribed here by me, but I note it because it may be a clue to this obscure passage. 
--><!-- 
None of the previous editors note that the śa of niveśanāni in l15 is added below the line, between ve and nā. 
--><!-- 
Mirashi notes that the ca in l15 is superfluous. He may be right, but the intent was probably something like "together with an abhyantarapuraniveśana _and_ four karṣaka-niveśanas". 
--><!-- 
All previous editors read catvāra without a visarga in l15, Mirashi and Sircar emending to catvāri and Gupte taking catvārabhuktakābhoga to be the name of the field that was donated. 
--><!-- 
For śāsanenosatibaddhaṁ in l16, Mirashi reads this without an anusvāra (unless it's lost in my scan). I can't see what he wants to emend to; in his notation it is śāsaneno[na] sati(ni)baddha(ddhaM). There is certainly no unclear na after the no, so he probably meant na as an emendation of no, in which case his emended text would be śāsanena sanibaddhaM, which doesn't seem to make much sense. Sircar suggests the emendation śāsanena pratibaddhāni; I don't see why he wants a plural. I think the original intent was most likely śāsanenopanibaddhaṁ. (Or, it's a very big blunder for śāsanenātisr̥ṣṭaṁ...) 
--><!-- 
The punctuation sign in l16 is a dash, not very short, near baseline height. So are others transcribed as single daṇḍas. 
--><!-- 
In l17 Mirashi reads cāturvidya and maryādān; rvv and ryy are both clear in the facsimile. 
--><!-- 
Line 17 does not reach the margin, but the scribe clearly didn't want to begin the list in such a short space, preferring to keep it as one chunk. 
--><!-- 
In l21 Sircar reads paitrānugāmī (emending to pautrā°). I go with Gupte and Mirashi and think the third stroke of au is visible as a dot near the bottom right of p. 
--><!-- 
Line 23, the last on the page, is squeezed into rather less vertical space than needed, so some of the bottoms of characters are at the extreme edge, while many of the vowel mātrās are compressed and/or interfere with the bottoms of characters in the previous line. 
--></p>
